arch:property.oc:show_val: l fragment size is around 40mm and the mean perhaps 60mm, with thirteen recently broken specimens nonetheless exceeding 100mm. Efforts to refit were limited by a substantial amount of missing material, a point which should also be borne in mind when assessing the overall size of the unit. At first glance the assemblage is dominated by large pieces of cattle-sized material, but on closer inspection smaller sheep-sized fragments probably contribute approaching 50% of INDEPENDENT specimens. There are also a complete rodent mandible and a fox phalanx, along with two hare-sized rib fragments. The cattle-sized material is mostly cattle where determinate, although there is also a single large cervid antler beam and a probable equid mandible fragment. This fraction has a very distinctive composition, being dominated by large pieces of rib (5+), scapula (2+), pelvis (2+), horn core (1+), and cervical vertebra (2+). With the exception of the latter, and along with antler, these are all particularly common elements within space 337 and the adjacent 338, especially on/near the floor. Two of the rib pieces exceed 30cm. Other cattle-sized material includes a cattle astragalus and femur shaft fragment, a cattle nasal, a premaxilla, and a (small) cattle-sized distal humerus splinter. The latter is in very different condition from the rest (unburnt, heavily gnawed) and may be intrusive - some animal burrowing is noted on the unit sheet. The composition of the sheep-sized fraction is less distinctive. The majority of specimens are appendicular or cranial, with only a few rib pieces, two fragments of pelvis (probably the same bone in the ground) and no vertebrae. Long bone scrap constitutes around 50% of this fraction. Most of the determinate appendicular specimens are humeri (4) or metacarpals (3 + 1 worked), along with a scapula, phalanx and tibia. The sample is probably too small to read anything into this. Cranial specimens include skull fragments and at least two mandibles. Unsurprisingly given its provenience, the unit is almost entirely burnt. More surprising is the variety of burning conditions that are represented, and the fact that a little over 5% of the material shows little or no visible sign of burning. This is probably not intrusive given that most unburnt fragments probably belong to a single large piece of partly carbonized cattle-sized rib, which appears very much an integral part of the unit, but is hard to explain. The type of burning is split fairly evenly between carbonization, classic calcination (i.e. white) and a dull grey calcination that presumably represents heating in reducing conditions. Much of the completely calcined (white) material also features a strange light green colour reminiscent of copper, also noted on various clusters and bin fills within space 377. There is no digestion in the main sample (a few cases in the flot) and only one markedly gnawed specimen - the aforementioned distal humerus splinter - plus two or three lightly gnawed pieces. Surface condition is obviously affected to a great extent by burning, and the vast majority of burnt specimens are in good condition (stage 3/’slight weathering’). The unburnt pieces show considerable flaking and are mostly at stage 4 (‘moderate weathering’). The unit represents the lower fill of around 60% of space 337 (excluding the main northern bins) and it is likely that - as noted above - a significant amount of bone never made it to the faunal unit. The heterogeneity in terms of burning presumably indicates that different conditions obtained in different parts of the space. Given that feature collapse is thought to have made up the bulk of this unit, it is possible that some of the bones were covered early enough in the burning process to have been protected from oxidation, hence their grey-calcined appearance. This may also explain the unburnt pieces. The origin of the material is unclear, but is likely to have been varied. As noted above, antlers, cattle horn cores, and cattle-sized scapulae and ribs are common in Building 77 and in many cases appear to have been on the floor at the point of collapse, presumably either placed there or having fallen from the walls or ceiling. (16469) is close enough to the floor that some specimens may have become included from floor deposits, or alternatively could have been mixed in with feature rubble if suspended from the walls or ceiling at the start of the building destruction. Again, there is no reason to believe that all the material entered the unit in the same way. The ribs, scapulae, and antler in particular may represent raw materials for working, worked ribs having been noted elsewhere in the space. Flot (>4mm, 100%): the flot is very small (~45 fragments) and dominated by sheep-sized specimens, with a single cattle-sized rib splinter. These include a caprine patella, digested tarsal, cervical vertebra, scapula and long bone fragments. Surprisingly, unburnt specimens are rather more common than in the main sample, at about 15%, but otherwise condition is consistent.

arch:string.div: The unique identifier for each contextual unit, matching those used in the central Çatalhöyük excavation database and in publications. The excavation uses single-context recording.
